    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Drunken-Driving Law</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>MADD Long Island president Dee Cornella letter on June 19 editorial listing issues still facing New York State Legislature cites anti-drunken-driving laws</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Albany's Work Is Not Done'' (editorial, June 19):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Albany's Work Is Not Done'' (editorial, June 19):</p>
        <p>Of all the work mentioned as ''undone,'' you overlooked the anti-drunken-driving measures, which draw a lot of rhetoric but little action.</p>
        <p>Although lowering the illegal intoxication level from .10 to .08 blood alcohol content has been passed in separate bills by the Senate and the Assembly, the two houses have still failed to reconcile on a single bill for passage.</p>
        <p>Paramount among other vital issues are creating the crime of aggravated D.W.I. (stiffer penalties for driving with a blood alcohol content of .16 or higher); permanent license revocation for persistent D.W.I. offenders; and carrying out a statewide ignition interlock program.</p>
        <p>These are lifesaving measures that merit action by every legislator for the safety of everyone on our roadways.</p>
        <p>DEE CORNELLA  President, MADD Long Island  Huntington Station, N.Y.  June 20, 2002</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
